{{short description|1872 painting by Jean-Léon Gérôme}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Jean-Leon Gerome Pollice Verso.jpg | title=Pollice Verso | artist=[[Jean-Léon Gérôme]] | year=1872 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=96.5 | width_metric=149.2 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[United States]] | museum=[[Phoenix Art Museum]] }} '''''Pollice Verso''''' (from {{lang-la|with a turned thumb}}) is a painting by French artist [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]], featuring the [[Pollice verso|eponymous Roman gesture]] directed to the winning [[gladiator]]s.
The gesture on the painting is given by the [[Vestals]] to the victorious [[murmillo]], awaiting the decision on the beaten [[retiarius]] at the [[Colosseum]]. The painting inspired the 2000 film ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'', where [[Commodus]] holds out a raised thumb to spare [[Maximus Decimus Meridius|Maximus]].{{Citation needed|reason=The reference below is now dead and was not from reliable source;|date=November 2018}}
==The painting== Apart from the gladiators and Vestals, the picture shows the [[Roman emperor|emperor]] in his box. Gérôme deliberately used the light and [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] to depict some features. The blend of [[voyeurism]] and a sense of moral superiority is a specific 19th-century feature.<ref name="KEJ">Eckart Köhne, Cornelia Ewigleben, Ralph Jackson. ''Gladiators and Caesars: the power of spectacle in ancient Rome'', University of California Press, 2000, p. 31.</ref>
===History=== [[Alexander Turney Stewart]] purchased the painting from Gérôme and exhibited it in [[New York City]]. He published a [[pamphlet]] about the work, proving to the satisfaction of his contemporaries that ''pollice verso'' was a matter of turning the thumb up or down.<ref name="WCG">{{cite web|url=http://www.allartclassic.com/pictures_zoom.php?p_number=52&p=&number=GEJ001|title= Gerome Art Reproductions- Pollice Verso |publisher = World Classic Gallery|author= |accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref>
===Historical accuracy=== Gérôme's depiction of Colosseum's architecture is based on accurate drawings and the armour of gladiators follows the design of those found in [[Pompeii]].<ref name="KEJ"/> Gérôme also checked the written sources for archaeological reference. Some Latin textbooks used ''Pollice Verso'' to illustrate Roman customs.<ref name="WCG"/>
===Influence=== The producers of ''Gladiator'' showed [[Ridley Scott]] a reproduction of ''Pollice Verso'' before he read the film script. "That image spoke to me of the Roman Empire in all its glory and wickedness. I knew right then and there I was hooked", said Scott.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsgalleries.com/pollice-verso-thumbs-down/|title= Pollice Verso – Thumbs Down|publisher = Kings Galleries|author= |accessdate=2010-04-24}}</ref> However it was found that the secutor's armour is not properly assembled.<ref name="KEJ"/>
